014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"1994\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Must Have Been the Wind\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/must-have-been-the-wind-single/1467276993|title=Must Have Been the Wind \u2013 Single by Alec Benjamin|website=Apple Music|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2019\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"6\"| ''These Two Windows''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Jesus in LA\"<ref>{{cite tweet|user=AlecBenjamin|number=1148692015426596864|title=jesus in la. out everywhere tmrw . 9:30 am PST . \ud83d\ude2c . tune in to hear my interview with @zanelowe on @beats1 at 9am PST|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Mind Is a Prison\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/mind-is-a-prison-single/1488956818|title=Mind Is a Prison \u2013 Single by Alec Benjamin|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=row| \"Demons\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2020\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=row| \"Oh My God\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=row| \"The Book of You & I\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"font-size:85%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes a single that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://alecbenjamin.com/ Official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benjamin, Alec}}\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Dojazervas", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed song title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alec_Benjamin"}
{"title_page": "Martin Linton", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Martin Linton\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Martin Linton MP.JPG\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Battersea (UK Parliament constituency)|Battersea]]\n| parliament = \n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[John Bowis]]\n| successor = [[Jane Ellison]]\n| term_start = 1 May 1997\n| term_end = 12 April 2010\n| birth_place = [[Stockholm, Sweden]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date and age|1944|08|11|df=y}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Pembroke College, Oxford]]}}\n\n'''John Martin Linton''' (born 11 August 1944) is a [[Labour Party (UK)|British Labour Party]] politician, who was the Member of Parliament for [[Battersea (UK Parliament constituency)|Battersea]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].\n\n==Early life==\nLinton attended Limpsfield Primary School in [[Limpsfield]], Surrey; [[Christ's Hospital]] school in [[Horsham]], Sussex; and [[Pembroke College, Oxford]] gaining an [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA]] in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics|PPE]]; and [[University of Lyon|Universit\u00e9 de Lyon]]. Prior to becoming an MP, Linton was a [[journalist]] for the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' from 1981\u201397, and was a councillor in [[London Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth]] from 1971\u201382.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nDuring his career in journalism, he worked for ''[[Daily Mail]]'' (1966\u201371), ''[[The Financial Times]]'', ''Labour Weekly'' (1971\u201379) and the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'' (1980\u201381).{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe served as a [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Baroness Blackstone]] in the [[Department of Culture, Media and Sport]] (DCMS) from 2001\u20133, and to [[Peter Hain]] as [[Leader of the House of Commons]] from 2003 to 2005. After the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]] he was made a [[Parliamentary Private Secretary|PPS]] again, this time in the [[Department for Constitutional Affairs]] (DCA).\n\nHe is Treasurer of British-Swedish Parliamentary Association and Vice-Chairman of All-Party British-Swedish Group, reflecting his [[Sweden|Swedish]] roots.\n\nAfter the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]], his majority stood at 163, one of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Commons']] smallest in that parliament.\n\nHe visited the West Bank and Gaza in September 2007 with the Britain-Palestine All Party Parliamentary Group. Following that visit, Linton founded and currently chairs Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East.<ref>[http://www.labourfriendsofpalestine.co.uk/?page_id=18 Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The organisation is committed to a two-state solution with secure Palestinian and Israeli states. He has visited Israel and Gaza three times to campaign for peace talks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.martinlinton.org.uk/about-us/|title=About Us}}</ref>\n\nActive on a number of environmental issues, he successfully lobbied the government to target a cut of 80% in Carbon emissions by 2050 rather than a cut of 60%.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martins-policy-qa---ask-martin-a-question] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501100901/http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martins-policy-qa---ask-martin-a-question |date=1 May 2010 }}</ref> Linton opposed plans to build a third runway at Heathrow<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martin-welcomes-high-court-decision-on-third-runway]{{dead link|date=January 2011}}</ref> He signed a number of [[Early Day Motions]] supporting tougher action on environmental issues and has promised to reduce his personal carbon emissions by 10% as part of the [[10:10]] campaign.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/climate-change-policy]{{dead link|date=January 2011}}</ref>\n\nLinton has campaigned for electoral reform for a number of years and wrote ''Labour's Road to Electoral Reform: What's Wrong with First-Past-the-Post?'' (with Mary Georghiou, 1993) and ''Making Votes Count: The Case for Electoral Reform'' (1998). The government backed one of Martin's amendments in February 2010<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_8492000/8492695.stm \"Brown to outline vote change bid\"], BBC News Today website, 2 February 2010</ref> which puts the Labour party's commitment to a referendum on the [[Instant-runoff voting|alternative vote]] system into legislation.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/government-backs-linton-alternative-vote-amendment] \"Government Backs Linton vote amendmebnt\"], Martin Linton's website, [February 2010] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429103056/http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/government-backs-linton-alternative-vote-amendment |date=29 April 2010 }}</ref> Linton does not believe that tax exiles<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment/opinion-former-index/legal-and-constitutional/comment-a-lot-to-play-for-$1310230.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122112111/http://www.politics.co.uk/comment/opinion-former-index/legal-and-constitutional/comment-a-lot-to-play-for-%241310230.htm|url-status=dead|title=Comment: A lot to play for<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=22 January 2010}}</ref> should be able to donate to political parties, and has lobbied for an enquiry into whether [[Lord Ashcroft]] breached the [[House of Lords]] code of conduct.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martin-linton-demands-ashcroft-enquiry]{{dead link|date=January 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe voted for MPs' expenses to be made more transparent since 2007.,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Martin_Linton&mpc=Battersea&dmp=996&display=motions|title=Martin Linton compared to 'Transparency of Parliament'|website=www.publicwhip.org.uk}}</ref> and was ranked the 13th lowest spending MP by an independent think tank<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/expenses] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501101116/http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/expenses |date=1 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, Linton drew criticism for remarks he made to a meeting at the House of Commons held by the Palestine Solidarity \nCampaign and Friends of al-Aqsa, in which he stated that: \n<blockquote>\n\u201cThere are long tentacles of Israel in this country who are funding election campaigns and putting money into the British political system for their own ends...when you make decisions about how you vote and how you advise constituents to vote, you must make them aware of the attempt by Israelis and by pro-Israelis to influence the election.\u201d<ref>[http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/30000/mp-israels-tentacles-will-steal-election By Martin Bright and Robyn Rosen, ''The JC'', March 29, 2010.]</ref></blockquote>\n\nAt the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]], he lost his seat to [[Jane Ellison]] of the Conservative Party.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe lives in Battersea with his wife Sara (married July 2008) and his two stepdaughters. His first wife Kathy, with whom he had two children (now grown-up), died in 1995.<br>\n[[Sydney Linton|His great-grandfather]] was the inaugural [[Anglican Diocese of Riverina|Bishop of Riverina]], [[New South Wales]], Australia.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-martin-linton | Martin Linton }}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-3146,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Martin Linton MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/martin_linton/battersea TheyWorkForYou.com \u2013 Martin Linton MP]\n* [http://battersea-mp.org.uk/ The Unofficial Martin Linton Weblog]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081202104843/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/35.stm BBC Politics]\n*[https://www.martinlinton.org.uk/ Martin Linton] official site\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Battersea (UK Parliament constituency)|Battersea]]\n  | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] \u2013 [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n  | before = [[John Bowis]]\n  | after  = [[Jane Ellison]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linton, Martin}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Christ's Hospital]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Nuffield College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Martin Linton\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Martin Linton MP.JPG\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Battersea (UK Parliament constituency)|Battersea]]\n| parliament = \n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[John Bowis]]\n| successor = [[Jane Ellison]]\n| term_start = 1 May 1997\n| term_end = 12 April 2010\n| birth_place = [[Stockholm, Sweden]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date and age|1944|08|11|df=y}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Pembroke College, Oxford]]}}\n\n'''John Martin Linton''' (born 11 August 1944) is a [[Labour Party (UK)|British Labour Party]] politician, who was the Member of Parliament for [[Battersea (UK Parliament constituency)|Battersea]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].\n\n==Early life==\nLinton attended Limpsfield Primary School in [[Limpsfield]], Surrey; [[Christ's Hospital]] school in [[Horsham]], Sussex; and [[Pembroke College, Oxford]] gaining an [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA]] in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics|PPE]]; and [[University of Lyon|Universit\u00e9 de Lyon]]. Prior to becoming an MP, Linton was a [[journalist]] for the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' from 1981\u201397, and was a councillor in [[London Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth]] from 1971-82.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nDuring his career in journalism, he worked for ''[[Daily Mail]]'' (1966\u201371), ''[[The Financial Times]]'', ''Labour Weekly'' (1971\u201379) and the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'' (1980\u201381).{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHe served as a [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Baroness Blackstone]] in the [[Department of Culture, Media and Sport]] (DCMS) from 2001\u20133, and to [[Peter Hain]] as [[Leader of the House of Commons]] from 2003 to 2005. After the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]] he was made a [[Parliamentary Private Secretary|PPS]] again, this time in the [[Department for Constitutional Affairs]] (DCA).\n\nHe is Treasurer of British-Swedish Parliamentary Association and Vice-Chairman of All-Party British-Swedish Group, reflecting his [[Sweden|Swedish]] roots.\n\nAfter the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]], his majority stood at 163, one of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Commons']] smallest in that parliament.\n\nHe visited the West Bank and Gaza in September 2007 with the Britain-Palestine All Party Parliamentary Group. Following that visit, Linton founded and currently chairs Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East.<ref>[http://www.labourfriendsofpalestine.co.uk/?page_id=18 Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The organisation is committed to a two-state solution with secure Palestinian and Israeli states. He has visited Israel and Gaza three times to campaign for peace talks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.martinlinton.org.uk/about-us/|title=About Us}}</ref>\n\nActive on a number of environmental issues, he successfully lobbied the government to target a cut of 80% in Carbon emissions by 2050 rather than a cut of 60%.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martins-policy-qa---ask-martin-a-question] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501100901/http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martins-policy-qa---ask-martin-a-question |date=1 May 2010 }}</ref> Linton opposed plans to build a third runway at Heathrow<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martin-welcomes-high-court-decision-on-third-runway]{{dead link|date=January 2011}}</ref> He signed a number of [[Early Day Motions]] supporting tougher action on environmental issues and has promised to reduce his personal carbon emissions by 10% as part of the [[10:10]] campaign.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/climate-change-policy]{{dead link|date=January 2011}}</ref>\n\nLinton has campaigned for electoral reform for a number of years and wrote ''Labour's Road to Electoral Reform: What's Wrong with First-Past-the-Post?'' (with Mary Georghiou, 1993) and ''Making Votes Count: The Case for Electoral Reform'' (1998). The government backed one of Martin's amendments in February 2010<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_8492000/8492695.stm \"Brown to outline vote change bid\"], BBC News Today website, 2 February 2010</ref> which puts the Labour party's commitment to a referendum on the [[Instant-runoff voting|alternative vote]] system into legislation.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/government-backs-linton-alternative-vote-amendment] \"Government Backs Linton vote amendmebnt\"], Martin Linton's website, [February 2010] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429103056/http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/government-backs-linton-alternative-vote-amendment |date=29 April 2010 }}</ref> Linton does not believe that tax exiles<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/comment/opinion-former-index/legal-and-constitutional/comment-a-lot-to-play-for-$1310230.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122112111/http://www.politics.co.uk/comment/opinion-former-index/legal-and-constitutional/comment-a-lot-to-play-for-%241310230.htm|url-status=dead|title=Comment: A lot to play for<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=22 January 2010}}</ref> should be able to donate to political parties, and has lobbied for an enquiry into whether [[Lord Ashcroft]] breached the [[House of Lords]] code of conduct.<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/martin-linton-demands-ashcroft-enquiry]{{dead link|date=January 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe voted for MPs' expenses to be made more transparent since 2007.,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Martin_Linton&mpc=Battersea&dmp=996&display=motions|title=Martin Linton compared to 'Transparency of Parliament'|website=www.publicwhip.org.uk}}</ref> and was ranked the 13th lowest spending MP by an independent think tank<ref>[http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/expenses] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501101116/http://www.martinlinton.org.uk/expenses |date=1 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, Linton drew criticism for remarks he made to a meeting at the House of Commons held by the Palestine Solidarity \nCampaign and Friends of al-Aqsa, in which he stated that: \n<blockquote>\n\u201cThere are long tentacles of Israel in this country who are funding election campaigns and putting money into the British political system for their own ends...when you make decisions about how you vote and how you advise constituents to vote, you must make them aware of the attempt by Israelis and by pro-Israelis to influence the election.\u201d<ref>[http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/30000/mp-israels-tentacles-will-steal-election By Martin Bright and Robyn Rosen, ''The JC'', March 29, 2010.]</ref></blockquote>\n\nAt the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]], he lost his seat to [[Jane Ellison]] of the Conservative Party.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe lives in Battersea with his wife Sara (married July 2008) and his two stepdaughters. His first wife Kathy, with whom he had two children (now grown-up), died in 1995.<br>\n[[Sydney Linton|His great-grandfather]] was the inaugural [[Anglican Diocese of Riverina|Bishop of Riverina]], [[New South Wales]], Australia.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-martin-linton | Martin Linton }}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-3146,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Martin Linton MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/martin_linton/battersea TheyWorkForYou.com \u2013 Martin Linton MP]\n* [http://battersea-mp.org.uk/ The Unofficial Martin Linton Weblog]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081202104843/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/35.stm BBC Politics]\n*[https://www.martinlinton.org.uk/ Martin Linton] official site\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Member of Parliament for [[Battersea (UK Parliament constituency)|Battersea]]\n  | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] \u2013 [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n  | before = [[John Bowis]]\n  | after  = [[Jane Ellison]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linton, Martin}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Christ's Hospital]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Nuffield College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1971-82 \u2192 1971\u201382", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Linton"}
{"title_page": "Elias David Curiel", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Venezuelan poet and writer}}\n'''Elias David Curiel''' (9 August 1871 \u2013 28 September 1924) was a Venezuelan poet and writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/image/portrait-of-poet-jose-david-curiel-coro-venezuela-1980|title=Portrait of poet Jose David Curiel, Coro, Venezuela, 1980|website='Museum of The Jewish People \u2013 Beit Hatfutsot':'\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05d5\u05e6\u05d5\u05ea \u2013 \u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05d9\u05d0\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e2\u05dd \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9'|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gibralfaro.uma.es/criticalit/pag_1641.htm|title=\"El\u00edas David Curiel, precursor del Modernismo en Venezuela\" por Mar\u00eda Cristina Solaeche Galera|website=gibralfaro.uma.es|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was the son of David Curiel and Exilda Abenatar de Curiel.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arbell|first=Mordehay|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=T3t__sdb_SkC&pg=PA353&lpg=PA353&dq=curiel+family+elias+david&source=bl&ots=qKSxIJFOsx&sig=ACfU3U2AiBRCeVgWtv0BcavT4XEbTQQCxw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjFtsXQz_HnAhVRXRUIHfj4DAcQ6AEwAnoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=curiel%20family%20elias%20david&f=false|title=The Jewish Nation of the Caribbean: The Spanish-Portuguese Jewish Settlements in the Caribbean and the Guianas|date=2002|publisher=Gefen Publishing House Ltd|isbn=978-965-229-279-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was one of the first collaborators of the Corian weekly ''\"El Obrero\".'' He is considered one of the most prominent Venezuelan poets of the twentieth century. And had poems published in the magazine ''El Cojo Ilustrado''  on several occasions, in the edition N \u00b0 347 (published in 1906) a complete page is dedicated to him and from that moment on he came to collaborate with what was one of the most prominent print media companies of the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://literaturavirtual.angelfire.com/SOLAECHE91.htm|title=Elias David Curiel|website=literaturavirtual.angelfire.com|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Etn\u00f3logo|first=Jos\u00e9 Millet Escritor y|title=Curiel, El\u00edas David...jud\u00edo, poeta de Coro|url=https://www.academia.edu/15910929/Curiel_El%C3%ADas_David...jud%C3%ADo_poeta_de_Coro}}</ref>\n\nCuriel studied at the [[University of Zulia|Federal College]]. He is the founding director of Choir College and \u2013 with the poet Antonio Jos\u00e9 Hermoso \u2013 co-creator of a weekly newspaper, ''La Cantera''. He also served as editor-in-chief of the newspaper ''El D\u00eda.'' <!-- owned by Emilio Ram\u00edrez -->\n\nEl\u00edas David Curiel is also the author of the lyrics of the state anthem [[Falc\u00f3n]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noticialdia.com/2019/08/un-9-de-agosto-nacio-el-poeta-elias-david-curiel-autor-del-himno-de-falcon/|title=Un 9 de agosto naci\u00f3 el poeta, El\u00edas David Curiel, autor del himno de Falc\u00f3n|website=noticialdia.com|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curiel, Elias David}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan Jews]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:20th-century poets]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan poets]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century writers]]\n[[Category:University of Zulia alumni]]\n[[Category:Curiel family]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Venezuelan poet and writer}}\n'''Elias David Curiel''' (9 August 1871 \u2013 28 September 1924) was a Venezuelan poet and writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/image/portrait-of-poet-jose-david-curiel-coro-venezuela-1980|title=Portrait of poet Jose David Curiel, Coro, Venezuela, 1980|website='Museum of The Jewish People \u2013 Beit Hatfutsot':'\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05d5\u05e6\u05d5\u05ea \u2013 \u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05d9\u05d0\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e2\u05dd \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9'|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gibralfaro.uma.es/criticalit/pag_1641.htm|title=\"El\u00edas David Curiel, precursor del Modernismo en Venezuela\" por Mar\u00eda Cristina Solaeche Galera|website=gibralfaro.uma.es|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was the son of David Curiel and Exilda Abenatar de Curiel.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arbell|first=Mordehay|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=T3t__sdb_SkC&pg=PA353&lpg=PA353&dq=curiel+family+elias+david&source=bl&ots=qKSxIJFOsx&sig=ACfU3U2AiBRCeVgWtv0BcavT4XEbTQQCxw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjFtsXQz_HnAhVRXRUIHfj4DAcQ6AEwAnoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=curiel%20family%20elias%20david&f=false|title=The Jewish Nation of the Caribbean: The Spanish-Portuguese Jewish Settlements in the Caribbean and the Guianas|date=2002|publisher=Gefen Publishing House Ltd|isbn=978-965-229-279-7|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was one of the first collaborators of the Corian weekly ''\"El Obrero\".'' He is considered one of the most prominent Venezuelan poets of the twentieth century. And had poems published in the magazine ''El Cojo Ilustrado''  on several occasions, in the edition N \u00b0 347 (published in 1906) a complete page is dedicated to him and from that moment on he came to collaborate with what was one of the most prominent print media companies of the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://literaturavirtual.angelfire.com/SOLAECHE91.htm|title=Elias David Curiel|website=literaturavirtual.angelfire.com|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Etn\u00f3logo|first=Jos\u00e9 Millet Escritor y|title=Curiel, El\u00edas David...jud\u00edo, poeta de Coro|url=https://www.academia.edu/15910929/Curiel_El%C3%ADas_David...jud%C3%ADo_poeta_de_Coro}}</ref>\n\nCuriel studied at the [[University of Zulia|Federal College]]. He is the founding director of Choir College and \u2013 with the poet Antonio Jos\u00e9 Hermoso \u2013 co-creator of a weekly newspaper, ''La Cantera''. He also served as editor-in-chief of the newspaper ''El D\u00eda.'' <!-- owned by Emilio Ram\u00edrez -->\n\nEl\u00edas David Curiel is also the author of the lyrics of the state anthem [[Falc\u00f3n]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noticialdia.com/2019/08/un-9-de-agosto-nacio-el-poeta-elias-david-curiel-autor-del-himno-de-falcon/|title=Un 9 de agosto naci\u00f3 el poeta, El\u00edas David Curiel, autor del himno de Falc\u00f3n|website=noticialdia.com|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curiel, Elias David}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan Jews]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews]]\n[[Category:20th-century poets]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan poets]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century writers]]\n[[Category:University of Zulia alumni]]\n[[Category:Curiel family]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedunderlinkedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elias_David_Curiel"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Lansley", "text_new": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Lansley\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Lansley crop 2.jpg\n|office           = [[Leader of the House of Commons]]\n|primeminister    = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start       = 4 September 2012\n|term_end         = 14 July 2014\n|predecessor      = [[Sir George Young|George Young]]\n|successor        = [[William Hague]]\n|office1          = [[Lord Privy Seal|Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal]]\n|primeminister1   = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start1      = 4 September 2012\n|term_end1        = 14 July 2014\n|predecessor1     = [[Sir George Young|George Young]]\n|successor1       = [[Tina Stowell, Baroness Stowell of Beeston|The Baroness Stowell of Beeston]]\n|office2          = [[Secretary of State for Health]]\n|primeminister2   = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start2      = 12 May 2010\n|term_end2        = 4 September 2012\n|predecessor2     = [[Andy Burnham]]\n|successor2       = [[Jeremy Hunt]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|[[Shadow Cabinet of David Cameron|Shadow Cabinet positions]]}}\n|office3          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]\n|leader3          = [[Michael Howard]]<br>[[David Cameron]]\n|term_start3      = 19 June 2004\n|term_end3        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor3     = [[Tim Yeo]]\n|successor3       = [[Andy Burnham]]\n|office4          = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Shadow Minister for the Cabinet Office]]\n|leader4          = [[William Hague]]\n|term_start4      = 15 June 1999\n|term_end4        = 18 September 2001\n|preceded4        = Position established\n|succeeded4       = [[Tim Collins (politician)|Tim Collins]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n|office6          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]]\n|term_start6      = 1 May 1997\n|term_end6        = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor6     = Constituency established\n|successor6       = [[Heidi Allen]]\n|office5          =  [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>{{small|[[Lord Temporal]]}}\n|term_start5      = 5 October 2015<br>{{small|[[Life Peerage]]}}\n|term_end5        = \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1956|12|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Hornchurch]], England\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democrats]] {{small|(Before 1988)}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Toynbee |first=Polly |title=Some SDP thinking might strengthen Labour's nerve |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/mar/01/labour-unions-social-democracy-unions |accessdate=11 April 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 March 2011}}</ref><br>[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] {{small|(1988\u2013present)}}\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Exeter]]\n|spouse           = Marilyn Biggs {{small|(Divorced)}}<br>Sally Low\n|children         = 5\n|website          = {{url|andrewlansley.co.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Andrew David Lansley, Baron Lansley''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR-cats|size=100%|sep=,|CBE|PC|DL}} (born 11 December 1956) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician who previously served as [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care|Secretary of State for Health]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]]. He was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to 2015.\n\nLansley was born in [[Hornchurch]], Essex and studied Politics at the [[University of Exeter]]. He worked in the civil service before entering politics. He ran the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]] while at the Conservative Research Department and later was Vice-Chairman of the Conservative Party at the 2001 general election.\n\nLansley was the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]] from 2004 until 2010, the [[Secretary of State for Health]] from 2010 until 2012, and [[Leader of the House of Commons]] from 2012 until 2014. As Health Secretary, Lansley was responsible for the government's controversial [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]]. He announced his intention to stand down as an MP in 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Cabinet reshuffle: Andrew Lansley to step down at 2015 election|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/cabinet-reshuffle-andrew-lansley-to-step-down-at-2015-election-9608382.html|accessdate = 28 August 2015|date = 15 July 2014}}</ref> and was awarded a [[life peer]]age in the [[2015 Dissolution Honours]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dissolution Peerages 2015|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dissolution-peerages-2015|website=Gov.uk|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Hornchurch]], Essex, Lansley was educated at [[Brentwood School (Essex)|Brentwood School]] and the [[University of Exeter]], gaining a BA in politics. In 1977 while at Exeter University, Lansley was elected President of the Guild of Students (Student Union), as a [[Tory Reform Group]] candidate. His father Thomas worked in a pathology laboratory, and became co-founder of the Council for Professions Supplementary to Medicine and President of the Institute of Medical Laboratory Scientists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsj.nhs60.co.uk/page.cfm/link=32|title=Lansley reflects on 60 years of the NHS|website=Health Service Journal|accessdate=8 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nBefore entering politics, Lansley had \"a promising career in the civil service\".<ref name=BMJ/> Lansley worked for [[Norman Tebbit]] for three years as his [[private secretary]] at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]].<ref name=BMJ/> This encompassed the period of the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA's]] 1984 [[Brighton hotel bombing]] at the Conservative Party Conference in which Tebbit was seriously injured. Lansley and others have been praised by Tebbit for their support at that time.\n\nLansley went on to become more fully involved in politics. In 1990, he was appointed to run the [[Conservative Research Department]]. He ran the Conservative campaign for the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], which he describes as one of \"his proudest career achievements\"<ref>[http://www.andrewlansley.co.uk/index.php?pageid=4 About Andrew] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907032357/http://www.andrewlansley.co.uk/index.php?pageid=4 |date=7 September 2018 }} Andrew Lansley CBE MP. Retrieved 7 August 2009</ref> He suffered a minor stroke in 1992, initially misdiagnosed as an ear infection,<ref name=BMJ/> but made a full recovery save for permanently losing his sense of \"fine balance\".\n\nHe was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) for political service in the [[1996 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54255 |date=30 December 1995 |page=9  |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nLansley sought to enter parliament and was selected for the South Cambridgeshire seat where he was subsequently elected as an MP in 1997. He immediately joined the House of Commons health select committee.<ref name=BMJ>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.d491 |title=Andrew Lansley and his big gamble |journal=BMJ |volume=342 |pages=d491 |year=2011 |last1=Davies |first1=P }}</ref>\n\nAt the 2001 election he again took on a strategy role as a Vice-Chairman of the Conservative Party. As part of his duties Shadow Ministers had to clear the timing of their announcements with Lansley. He fitted them into a timetable known as the 'Stalingrid'. The 2001 election was not a success for the Conservative Party and party leader, [[William Hague]], resigned in its wake. [[Iain Duncan Smith]], the new leader, offered Lansley a position after the election but he turned this down and, until [[Michael Howard]] became Leader, Lansley was a backbencher.\n\nLansley was appointed a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] on 13 May 2010.<ref name=\"pc-13may2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/other/13th%20May2010%20List.doc |publisher=Privy Council Office |title=Orders for 13 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611044054/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/other/13th%20May2010%20List.doc |archivedate=11 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Shadow Cabinet==\nAfter Howard's election as party leader, Lansley soon returned to the Conservative frontbench. He served as the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]. In his post he developed policies centred on using choice to improve the [[National Health Service]], and was author of a chapter in Dr Tempest's 2006 book ''The Future of the NHS''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tempest|first1=Michelle|title=The Future of the NHS|date=2006|isbn=978-1-85811-369-2|url=http://www.thefutureofthenhs.com/book.html|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Cabinet minister==\nAfter becoming [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] in May 2010, [[David Cameron]] named Lansley as [[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] in the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition government]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/12/david-cameron-cabinet-posts-coalition |title=New cabinet posts dealt out in coalition government |website=The Guardian |date=12 May 2010}}</ref> A tempestuous two years of proposed health reforms followed.\n\nOn 4 September 2012, Lansley was moved to the positions of [[Lord Privy Seal]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]], which he retained until 14 July 2014. He was then replaced by [[William Hague]], following Hague's surprise resignation as Foreign Secretary, and retired from the Cabinet to the back benches, announcing the same day that he would not be seeking re-election to the House of Commons at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|next election]] and would hope to find an international role.<ref>Kashmira Gander, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/cabinet-reshuffle-andrew-lansley-to-step-down-at-2015-election-9608382.html Cabinet reshuffle: Andrew Lansley to step down at 2015 election] in ''[[The Independent]]'' dated 15 July 2015, accessed 2 January 2018</ref> In the event, the election came on 7 May 2015, and until his appointment to the [[House of Lords]] in October Lansley was out of parliament.\n\n===Proposed health reforms===\n{{Main|Health and Social Care Act 2012}}\n\nIn November 2010, Lansley provoked controversy by factoring into public health related bills representations from fast food companies such as [[McDonald's]], [[KFC]] and processed food and drink manufacturers [[PepsiCo]], [[Kellogg's]], [[Unilever]], [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars]] and [[Diageo]] on obesity, diet-related disease and alcohol, said by campaign groups{{which|date=May 2013}} to be the equivalent of handing smoking policy over to the tobacco industry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/nov/12/mcdonalds-pepsico-help-health-policy |title=McDonald's and PepsiCo to help write UK health policy |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/dec/09/health-policy-extent-corporate-influence |title=Health policy: extent of corporate influence revealed |website=The Guardian |date=9 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Ministers published the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|Health and Social Care Bill]], detailing [[National Health Service (England)#Current reform proposals|planned reforms]] that would pave the way for GP consortia to take over management of the NHS from [[Primary Care Trust]]s. Prime minister [[David Cameron]] said \"fundamental changes\" are needed in the NHS.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/2011/01/reforms-cameron-changes-needed |title=David Cameron defends NHS reforms |work=[[New Statesman]] |date=17 January 2011}}</ref> But doctors' leaders believed that GPs could simply have taken charge of PCTs instead, and achieved the same results.<ref name=UpheavealAvoided/> The reforms were intended to pave the way for groups of GPs to take control of NHS budgets, with the consortia to take charge in 2013 of about 80% of the funding and of planning and buying everything, from community health centres to hospital services. However, some specialist services such as neurosurgery would be provided by a national board.<ref name=UpheavealAvoided>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-12170336 |title=NHS upheaval could have been avoided, leading GPs say |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter to ''[[The Times]]'', [[British Medical Association]] chairman Hamish Meldrum, [[Royal College of Nursing]] chief executive Peter Carter, and the heads of the [[Unison]] and [[Unite the Union|Unite]] unions,  said the speed and scale of the reforms proposed risked undermining the care of patients by putting cost before quality.<ref name=UpheavealAvoided/> Criticism of the reforms had been mounting ahead of the publication of the Health and Social Care Bill on 19 January 2011.\n\nLansley's white paper on the NHS led to him being the subject of an unflattering [[hip hop]] track and video written by rapper NxtGen and poet Rob Gee, with the chorus \"Andrew Lansley, greedy / Andrew Lansley, [[wikt:tosser|tosser]] / the NHS is not for sale, you grey-haired [[wikt:manky|manky]] [[wikt:codger|codger]]\".<ref name=TakesRap/> It was picked up as one of the theme tunes to the anti-cuts movement and spawned placards at a [[March for the Alternative]] in March 2011.<ref name=YouTubeRap/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/mar/26/newcastle-bus-fight-cuts |title=Newcastle, 5am: the tired and weary take the bus south to fight the cuts |website=The Guardian |date=26 March 2011}}</ref> The video, partly paid for by Unison<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/2011/04/03/union-paid-for-andrew-lansley-rap-attack-115875-23035440/ |title=Union paid for Andrew Lansley rap attack |website=Daily Mirror |date=3 April 2011}}</ref> featured NxtGen rapping about Lansley's proposed GP commissioning policy, his part in the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|parliamentary expenses scandal]], and a controversial donation he had received from private health company [[Care UK]].<ref name=YouTubeRap>{{YouTube|Dl1jPqqTdNo|Andrew Lansley Rap}}.</ref> Lansley responded with a statement that he was \"impressed that he's managed to get lyrics about GP commissioning into a rap\", but stated \"We will never privatise the NHS\".<ref name=TakesRap>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/mar/25/andrew-lansley-rap-mc-nxtgen |title=Andrew Lansley takes rap from MC NxtGen over health policy in viral video |website=The Guardian |date=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the widespread criticism, on 4 April 2011, the Government announced a \"pause\" in the progress of the Health and Social Care Bill to allow the government to 'listen, reflect and improve' on the proposals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/apr/06/government-pause-listen-reflect-improve-nhs-reform |title=Government to \"pause, listen, reflect and improve\" NHS reform plans |website=The Guardian |date=6 April 2011 |accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Lansley faced more criticism<ref>{{cite news|title=Lansley Defends Video Message|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15833704 | work=BBC News | date=22 November 2011}}</ref> when he appeared speaking on a video played at NHS patients' bedside in England, the continuous loop video was played to patients as the main free content on the [[Hospedia]] system. When asked by [[Tom Blenkinsop]] <small>MP</small>, Lansley replied that he received no payment and there was no cost to the taxpayer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lansley Answers on Video Mesage|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm111130/text/111130w0003.htm}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 2011, 96 per cent of 497 delegates at the [[Royal College of Nursing]] conference backed a [[motion of no confidence]] questioning Andrew Lansley's handling of NHS reforms in England.<ref name=\"No confidence\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-13063285 |title=Lansley sorry as nurses pass 'no confidence' vote |last=Triggle |first=Nick |date=13 April 2011 |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414035635/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-13063285 |archivedate=14 April 2011 |url-status= live}}</ref> Later that day, Lansley met with 65 nurses at the same conference, and apologised by saying \"I am sorry if what I'm setting out to do hasn't communicated itself.\"<ref name=\"No confidence\" /> In May 2012, Lansley appeared at the Royal College of Nursing annual conference where he stated that although \"the number of qualified nurses has gone down by nearly 3,000... clinical staffing levels overall have gone up by nearly 4,000\". His comments at the conference were met with uproar from nurses and union members in the audience with heckling and some shouting \"liar\". The Royal College's general secretary, Dr Peter Carter criticised the health secretary's claim as being \"nonsense that there's more clinical staff than there was two years ago is just incorrect\" and later told the health secretary that currently \"There is a great deal of unhappiness\" amongst nurses and health care professionals, with a standing ovation from the audience.<ref name=\"RCN liar\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/14/andrew-lansley-called-liar-nurses-rcn |website=The Guardian |title=Andrew Lansley called \"Liar\" \u2013 Nurses (RCN) |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2012, doctors meeting at a [[British Medical Association]] conference voted in favour of calling for Andrew Lansley's resignation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/bma-demands-andrew-lansley-resignation-7896267.html |website=The Independent |title=BMA demands Andrew Landsley's resignation |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Doctors voted in agreement of a motion stating \"This meeting has no confidence in Andrew Lansley, the Secretary of State for Health, and calls for him to resign\". In the meeting, Lansley was accused by the BMA of \"breaching doctors' trust\" over pension agreements, and was accused by Dr Gary Marlowe who tabled the motion that \"during the election he (Lansley) misled the public and the profession\" regarding the Health and Social Care Bill. Before voting, Marlowe also stated that \"The Bill went through a stunning number of amendments and revisions. I believe the most of any Bill. How can we trust someone with such a poor record with our NHS?\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/9361821/BMA-conference-doctors-threaten-new-strike-over-pensions.html |website=The Daily Telegraph |title=BMA conference doctors threaten new strike over pensions |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012|last1=Smith |first1=Rebecca }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2012, Lansley was moved out of his role as Health Secretary into the position of [[Lord Privy Seal]].\n\n==Salt reduction==\nIn 2010 Nutrition policy was transferred to the Department of Health. As Secretary of State for Health, Andrew Lansley was accused by the BMJ of allowing the food industry to stall progress in reducing salt content in food (subsequently restarted in 2014 by [[Anna Soubry]] with publication of new targets effective in 2017).<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.h1936 |pmid=25922339 |title=Food and the responsibility deal: How the salt reduction strategy was derailed |journal=BMJ |volume=350 |pages=h1936 |year=2015 |last1=MacGregor |first1=G. A |last2=He |first2=F. J |last3=Pombo-Rodrigues |first3=S }}</ref>\n\n==Public behaviour==\n[[File:Lansley poster at 2011 protests.JPG|thumb|right|A poster critical of Lansley being carried during the [[2011 anti-cuts protest in London]].]]\n\n===Suggested conflicts of interest===\nUntil December 2009, Lansley received \u00a3134 an hour from a firm of advertisers that represents clients such as [[Walkers (snack foods)|Walkers Crisps]], [[McDonald's]], [[Unilever]], [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars]] and [[Pizza Hut]]; ''[[Private Eye]]'' suggests a link between these activities and Lansley's desire to see a more lightly regulated food industry.<ref name=\"pe1267\">{{cite magazine|title=HP Sauce|magazine=[[Private Eye]]|date=23 July \u2013 5 August 2010|issue=1267|page=6}}</ref> The same publication suggested a similar link to a Department of Health report on red meat in which the only products listed in the report found to contain suitable amounts of red meat to merit a \"Good\" rating were a ''McDonald's [[Big Mac]]'', and a [[Peperami]] (manufactured by Unilever).\n\nWhile in opposition as health spokesman, Andrew Lansley accepted a donation of \u00a321,000 from [[John Nash, Baron Nash|John Nash]], the chairman of private healthcare provider [[Care UK]] and founder of the private equity fund Sovereign Capital, which owns several other private healthcare companies, to help fund his private office, leading to allegations of a conflict of interest.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/6989408/Andrew-Lansley-bankrolled-by-private-healthcare-provider.html |title=Andrew Lansley bankrolled by private healthcare provider |website=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 January 2010 |accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref> Such companies stand to be the largest beneficiaries of Lansley's bill passed by the Coalition and [[House of Lords]] to increase the use of private health providers within the NHS.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Holly |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/6989408/Andrew-Lansley-bankrolled-by-private-healthcare-provider.html |title=Andrew Lansley bankrolled by private healthcare provider|work=The Daily Telegraph|date= 14 January 2010|accessdate=14 January 2011|location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110125054040/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/6989408/Andrew-Lansley-bankrolled-by-private-healthcare-provider.html| archivedate= 25 January 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs reported February 2011, Lansley's wife advised attendees at a business conference to \"establish positive relationships with decision-makers\". Although staff members of Low Associates, the PR firm she runs, had food and drug companies among their clients before joining Low Associates, the firm denies it has any clients in the health sector.<ref name=\"Wife lobbying\">{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Holly |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8305506/Wife-of-Health-Secretary-Andrew-Lansley-gave-lobbying-advice.html |title=Wife of Health Secretary Andrew Lansley gave lobbying advice |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 February 2011 |accessdate=30 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311013846/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8305506/Wife-of-Health-Secretary-Andrew-Lansley-gave-lobbying-advice.html|archivedate=11 March 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAndrew Lansley's wife, Sally Low, is the managing director of Low Associates. Sally Low denies that Low Associates is involved in lobbying and instead describes its activities as provision of \"strategic advice\" to clients. Low Associates helps people prepare before they give evidence to committees of MPs, and Sally Low has given speeches on improving lobbying skills, in which she said that lobbyists should \"establish positive relationships with decision-makers before you need their help\". Lobbyist clients of Low Associates personnel have previously worked for a variety of companies including those with an interest in health, such as [[GlaxoSmithKline|SmithKline Beecham]], Unilever and Procter & Gamble.<ref name=\"Wife lobbying\"/>\n\n===Recession===\nAndrew Lansley wrote a blog entry on the Conservative Party website on 25 November 2008, which claimed the \"good things\" from a recession included people being able to spend more time with their families.<ref>[http://www.recessmonkey.com/2008/11/25/lost-your-job-well-at-least-you-will-see-more-of-your-family/ Recess Monkey]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107151538/http://www.recessmonkey.com/2008/11/25/lost-your-job-well-at-least-you-will-see-more-of-your-family/ |date=7 January 2009 }}</ref> He was later forced to apologise.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7748085.stm | work=BBC News | title=Lansley's recession blog apology | date=25 November 2008 | accessdate=25 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary expenses===\nIn the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|Parliamentary expenses scandal]] in 2009, Lansley was accused of 'flipping', or redesignating, his second home, after claiming for renovation of a rural cottage prior to selling it. It is claimed that he then 'flipped' his second home designation to a London flat, and claimed thousands of pounds for furniture. Lansley responded to the claims by stating that his claims were \"within the rules\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rayner |first=Gordon |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5305406/Andrew-Lansley-sold-home-after-expenses-renovations.html |title=Andrew Lansley sold home after expenses renovations\n|work=The Daily Telegraph |date= 11 May 2009|accessdate=14 May 2009 |location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090514070251/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5305406/Andrew-Lansley-sold-home-after-expenses-renovations.html| archivedate= 14 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> He owns a Pimlico property, but has claimed over \u00a37000 for hotel stays.\n\n==House of Lords==\nLansley was created a [[Life Peer]] taking the title '''Baron Lansley''', ''of [[Orwell, Cambridgeshire|Orwell]] in the County of [[Cambridgeshire]]'' on 5 October 2015.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61375 |date=8 October 2015 |page=18926}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLansley married his first wife Marilyn Biggs in 1985 and they had three daughters.<ref name=\"walked\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/andrew-lansley-it-would-let-people-down-if-i-just-walked-away-6278843.html|title=Andrew Lansley: 'It would let people down if I just walked away'|last=Chorley|first=Matt|date=18 December 2011|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref> They divorced in 2001 and Lansley married Sally Low, with whom he has had a son and a daughter.<ref name=walked/> Lansley's wealth was estimated at \u00a3700,000 in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |author=Samira Shackle, Stephanie Hegarty and George Eaton |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2009/10/oxford-universitywealth-school |title = The new ruling class |work=New Statesman |date=1 October 2009|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 Lansley revealed that he has [[Cancer staging|stage 3]] [[bowel cancer]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Greenfield|first1=Patrick|title=Lord Lansley calls for better screening after revealing cancer|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/apr/03/lord-lansley-calls-for-better-screening-after-revealing-cancer|accessdate=3 April 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 April 2018}}</ref> He has called for the government to widen the [[cancer screening]] programme on the NHS.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andrew Lansley}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110729105138/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Lansley_Andrew.aspx Profile] at the Conservative Party\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = andrew-lansley/123 | hansard = mr-andrew-lansley | hansardcurr = 1419 | guardian = 3010/andrew-lansley | publicwhip = Andrew_Lansley | theywork = andrew_lansley | record = Andrew-Lansley/South-Cambridgeshire/286 | bbc = 25555.stm | journalisted = andrew-lansley }}\n*{{Guardian topic}}\n*[http://www.thefutureofthenhs.com The Future of the NHS]\n*[http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/20501/Andrew-David-LANSLEY ''Debrett's People of Today'']{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Heidi Allen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Shadow Minister for the Cabinet Office]]|years=1999\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tim Collins (politician)|Tim Collins]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Yeo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]|years=2004\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andy Burnham]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andy Burnham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Health]]|years=2010\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeremy Hunt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Sir George Young|George Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the House of Commons]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Hague]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Privy Seal]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Tina Stowell, Baroness Stowell of Beeston|The Baroness Stowell of Beeston]]}}}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stuart Polak, Baron Polak|The Lord Polak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Lansley'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Jonathan Oates, Baron Oates|The Lord Oates]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Cabinet of David Cameron}}\n{{Leader of the House of Commons}}\n{{Secretary of State for Health}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lansley, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Exeter]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Department of Trade and Industry]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by David Cameron]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brentwood School, Essex]]\n[[Category:People from Hornchurch]]\n[[Category:Private secretaries in the British Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Health (UK)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Lansley\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Lansley crop 2.jpg\n|office           = [[Leader of the House of Commons]]\n|primeminister    = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start       = 4 September 2012\n|term_end         = 14 July 2014\n|predecessor      = [[Sir George Young|George Young]]\n|successor        = [[William Hague]]\n|office1          = [[Lord Privy Seal|Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal]]\n|primeminister1   = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start1      = 4 September 2012\n|term_end1        = 14 July 2014\n|predecessor1     = [[Sir George Young|George Young]]\n|successor1       = [[Tina Stowell, Baroness Stowell of Beeston|The Baroness Stowell of Beeston]]\n|office2          = [[Secretary of State for Health]]\n|primeminister2   = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start2      = 12 May 2010\n|term_end2        = 4 September 2012\n|predecessor2     = [[Andy Burnham]]\n|successor2       = [[Jeremy Hunt]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|[[Shadow Cabinet of David Cameron|Shadow Cabinet positions]]}}\n|office3          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]\n|leader3          = [[Michael Howard]]<br>[[David Cameron]]\n|term_start3      = 19 June 2004\n|term_end3        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor3     = [[Tim Yeo]]\n|successor3       = [[Andy Burnham]]\n|office4          = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Shadow Minister for the Cabinet Office]]\n|leader4          = [[William Hague]]\n|term_start4      = 15 June 1999\n|term_end4        = 18 September 2001\n|preceded4        = Position established\n|succeeded4       = [[Tim Collins (politician)|Tim Collins]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n|office6          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]]\n|term_start6      = 1 May 1997\n|term_end6        = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor6     = Constituency established\n|successor6       = [[Heidi Allen]]\n|office5          =  [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>{{small|[[Lord Temporal]]}}\n|term_start5      = 5 October 2015<br>{{small|[[Life Peerage]]}}\n|term_end5        = \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1956|12|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Hornchurch]], England\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democrats]] {{small|(Before 1988)}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Toynbee |first=Polly |title=Some SDP thinking might strengthen Labour's nerve |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/mar/01/labour-unions-social-democracy-unions |accessdate=11 April 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 March 2011}}</ref><br>[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] {{small|(1988\u2013present)}}\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Exeter]]\n|spouse           = Marilyn Biggs {{small|(Divorced)}}<br>Sally Low\n|children         = 5\n|website          = {{url|andrewlansley.co.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Andrew David Lansley, Baron Lansley''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR-cats|size=100%|sep=,|CBE|PC|DL}} (born 11 December 1956) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician who previously served as [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care|Secretary of State for Health]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]]. He was [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to 2015.\n\nLansley was born in [[Hornchurch]], Essex and studied Politics at the [[University of Exeter]]. He worked in the civil service before entering politics. He ran the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]] while at the Conservative Research Department and later was Vice-Chairman of the Conservative Party at the 2001 general election.\n\nLansley was the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]] from 2004 until 2010, the [[Secretary of State for Health]] from 2010 until 2012, and [[Leader of the House of Commons]] from 2012 until 2014. As Health Secretary, Lansley was responsible for the government's controversial [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]]. He announced his intention to stand down as an MP in 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Cabinet reshuffle: Andrew Lansley to step down at 2015 election|url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/cabinet-reshuffle-andrew-lansley-to-step-down-at-2015-election-9608382.html|accessdate = 28 August 2015|date = 15 July 2014}}</ref> and was awarded a [[life peer]]age in the [[2015 Dissolution Honours]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dissolution Peerages 2015|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/dissolution-peerages-2015|website=Gov.uk|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Hornchurch]], Essex, Lansley was educated at [[Brentwood School (Essex)|Brentwood School]] and the [[University of Exeter]], gaining a BA in politics. In 1977 while at Exeter University, Lansley was elected President of the Guild of Students (Student Union), as a [[Tory Reform Group]] candidate. His father Thomas worked in a pathology laboratory, and became co-founder of the Council for Professions Supplementary to Medicine and President of the Institute of Medical Laboratory Scientists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsj.nhs60.co.uk/page.cfm/link=32|title=Lansley reflects on 60 years of the NHS|website=Health Service Journal|accessdate=8 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nBefore entering politics, Lansley had \"a promising career in the civil service\".<ref name=BMJ/> Lansley worked for [[Norman Tebbit]] for three years as his [[private secretary]] at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]].<ref name=BMJ/> This encompassed the period of the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA's]] 1984 [[Brighton hotel bombing]] at the Conservative Party Conference in which Tebbit was seriously injured. Lansley and others have been praised by Tebbit for their support at that time.\n\nLansley went on to become more fully involved in politics. In 1990, he was appointed to run the [[Conservative Research Department]]. He ran the Conservative campaign for the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], which he describes as one of \"his proudest career achievements\"<ref>[http://www.andrewlansley.co.uk/index.php?pageid=4 About Andrew] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907032357/http://www.andrewlansley.co.uk/index.php?pageid=4 |date=7 September 2018 }} Andrew Lansley CBE MP. Retrieved 7 August 2009</ref> He suffered a minor stroke in 1992, initially misdiagnosed as an ear infection,<ref name=BMJ/> but made a full recovery save for permanently losing his sense of \"fine balance\".\n\nHe was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) for political service in the [[1996 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54255 |date=30 December 1995 |page=9  |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nLansley sought to enter parliament and was selected for the South Cambridgeshire seat where he was subsequently elected as an MP in 1997. He immediately joined the House of Commons health select committee.<ref name=BMJ>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.d491 |title=Andrew Lansley and his big gamble |journal=BMJ |volume=342 |pages=d491 |year=2011 |last1=Davies |first1=P }}</ref>\n\nAt the 2001 election he again took on a strategy role as a Vice-Chairman of the Conservative Party. As part of his duties Shadow Ministers had to clear the timing of their announcements with Lansley. He fitted them into a timetable known as the 'Stalingrid'. The 2001 election was not a success for the Conservative Party and party leader, [[William Hague]], resigned in its wake. [[Iain Duncan Smith]], the new leader, offered Lansley a position after the election but he turned this down and, until [[Michael Howard]] became Leader, Lansley was a backbencher.\n\nLansley was appointed a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] on 13 May 2010.<ref name=\"pc-13may2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/other/13th%20May2010%20List.doc |publisher=Privy Council Office |title=Orders for 13 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611044054/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/other/13th%20May2010%20List.doc |archivedate=11 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Shadow Cabinet==\nAfter Howard's election as party leader, Lansley soon returned to the Conservative frontbench. He served as the [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]. In his post he developed policies centred on using choice to improve the [[National Health Service]], and was author of a chapter in Dr Tempest\u2019s 2006 book ''The Future of the NHS''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tempest|first1=Michelle|title=The Future of the NHS|date=2006|isbn=978-1-85811-369-2|url=http://www.thefutureofthenhs.com/book.html|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Cabinet minister==\nAfter becoming [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] in May 2010, [[David Cameron]] named Lansley as [[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] in the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition government]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/12/david-cameron-cabinet-posts-coalition |title=New cabinet posts dealt out in coalition government |website=The Guardian |date=12 May 2010}}</ref> A tempestuous two years of proposed health reforms followed.\n\nOn 4 September 2012, Lansley was moved to the positions of [[Lord Privy Seal]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]], which he retained until 14 July 2014. He was then replaced by [[William Hague]], following Hague's surprise resignation as Foreign Secretary, and retired from the Cabinet to the back benches, announcing the same day that he would not be seeking re-election to the House of Commons at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|next election]] and would hope to find an international role.<ref>Kashmira Gander, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/cabinet-reshuffle-andrew-lansley-to-step-down-at-2015-election-9608382.html Cabinet reshuffle: Andrew Lansley to step down at 2015 election] in ''[[The Independent]]'' dated 15 July 2015, accessed 2 January 2018</ref> In the event, the election came on 7 May 2015, and until his appointment to the [[House of Lords]] in October Lansley was out of parliament.\n\n===Proposed health reforms===\n{{Main|Health and Social Care Act 2012}}\n\nIn November 2010, Lansley provoked controversy by factoring into public health related bills representations from fast food companies such as [[McDonald's]], [[KFC]] and processed food and drink manufacturers [[PepsiCo]], [[Kellogg's]], [[Unilever]], [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars]] and [[Diageo]] on obesity, diet-related disease and alcohol, said by campaign groups{{which|date=May 2013}} to be the equivalent of handing smoking policy over to the tobacco industry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/nov/12/mcdonalds-pepsico-help-health-policy |title=McDonald's and PepsiCo to help write UK health policy |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/dec/09/health-policy-extent-corporate-influence |title=Health policy: extent of corporate influence revealed |website=The Guardian |date=9 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Ministers published the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|Health and Social Care Bill]], detailing [[National Health Service (England)#Current reform proposals|planned reforms]] that would pave the way for GP consortia to take over management of the NHS from [[Primary Care Trust]]s. Prime minister [[David Cameron]] said \"fundamental changes\" are needed in the NHS.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/2011/01/reforms-cameron-changes-needed |title=David Cameron defends NHS reforms |work=[[New Statesman]] |date=17 January 2011}}</ref> But doctors' leaders believed that GPs could simply have taken charge of PCTs instead, and achieved the same results.<ref name=UpheavealAvoided/> The reforms were intended to pave the way for groups of GPs to take control of NHS budgets, with the consortia to take charge in 2013 of about 80% of the funding and of planning and buying everything, from community health centres to hospital services. However, some specialist services such as neurosurgery would be provided by a national board.<ref name=UpheavealAvoided>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-12170336 |title=NHS upheaval could have been avoided, leading GPs say |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter to ''[[The Times]]'', [[British Medical Association]] chairman Hamish Meldrum, [[Royal College of Nursing]] chief executive Peter Carter, and the heads of the [[Unison]] and [[Unite the Union|Unite]] unions,  said the speed and scale of the reforms proposed risked undermining the care of patients by putting cost before quality.<ref name=UpheavealAvoided/> Criticism of the reforms had been mounting ahead of the publication of the Health and Social Care Bill on 19 January 2011.\n\nLansley's white paper on the NHS led to him being the subject of an unflattering [[hip hop]] track and video written by rapper NxtGen and poet Rob Gee, with the chorus \"Andrew Lansley, greedy / Andrew Lansley, [[wikt:tosser|tosser]] / the NHS is not for sale, you grey-haired [[wikt:manky|manky]] [[wikt:codger|codger]]\".<ref name=TakesRap/> It was picked up as one of the theme tunes to the anti-cuts movement and spawned placards at a [[March for the Alternative]] in March 2011.<ref name=YouTubeRap/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/mar/26/newcastle-bus-fight-cuts |title=Newcastle, 5am: the tired and weary take the bus south to fight the cuts |website=The Guardian |date=26 March 2011}}</ref> The video, partly paid for by Unison<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/2011/04/03/union-paid-for-andrew-lansley-rap-attack-115875-23035440/ |title=Union paid for Andrew Lansley rap attack |website=Daily Mirror |date=3 April 2011}}</ref> featured NxtGen rapping about Lansley's proposed GP commissioning policy, his part in the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|parliamentary expenses scandal]], and a controversial donation he had received from private health company [[Care UK]].<ref name=YouTubeRap>{{YouTube|Dl1jPqqTdNo|Andrew Lansley Rap}}.</ref> Lansley responded with a statement that he was \"impressed that he's managed to get lyrics about GP commissioning into a rap\", but stated \"We will never privatise the NHS\".<ref name=TakesRap>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/mar/25/andrew-lansley-rap-mc-nxtgen |title=Andrew Lansley takes rap from MC NxtGen over health policy in viral video |website=The Guardian |date=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the widespread criticism, on 4 April 2011, the Government announced a \"pause\" in the progress of the Health and Social Care Bill to allow the government to 'listen, reflect and improve' on the proposals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/apr/06/government-pause-listen-reflect-improve-nhs-reform |title=Government to \"pause, listen, reflect and improve\" NHS reform plans |website=The Guardian |date=6 April 2011 |accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Lansley faced more criticism<ref>{{cite news|title=Lansley Defends Video Message|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-15833704 | work=BBC News | date=22 November 2011}}</ref> when he appeared speaking on a video played at NHS patients' bedside in England, the continuous loop video was played to patients as the main free content on the [[Hospedia]] system. When asked by [[Tom Blenkinsop]] <small>MP</small>, Lansley replied that he received no payment and there was no cost to the taxpayer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lansley Answers on Video Mesage|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm111130/text/111130w0003.htm}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April 2011, 96 per cent of 497 delegates at the [[Royal College of Nursing]] conference backed a [[motion of no confidence]] questioning Andrew Lansley's handling of NHS reforms in England.<ref name=\"No confidence\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-13063285 |title=Lansley sorry as nurses pass 'no confidence' vote |last=Triggle |first=Nick |date=13 April 2011 |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414035635/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-13063285 |archivedate=14 April 2011 |url-status= live}}</ref> Later that day, Lansley met with 65 nurses at the same conference, and apologised by saying \"I am sorry if what I'm setting out to do hasn't communicated itself.\"<ref name=\"No confidence\" /> In May 2012, Lansley appeared at the Royal College of Nursing annual conference where he stated that although \"the number of qualified nurses has gone down by nearly 3,000... clinical staffing levels overall have gone up by nearly 4,000\". His comments at the conference were met with uproar from nurses and union members in the audience with heckling and some shouting \"liar\". The Royal College's general secretary, Dr Peter Carter criticised the health secretary's claim as being \"nonsense that there's more clinical staff than there was two years ago is just incorrect\" and later told the health secretary that currently \"There is a great deal of unhappiness\" amongst nurses and health care professionals, with a standing ovation from the audience.<ref name=\"RCN liar\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/14/andrew-lansley-called-liar-nurses-rcn |website=The Guardian |title=Andrew Lansley called \"Liar\" \u2013 Nurses (RCN) |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2012, doctors meeting at a [[British Medical Association]] conference voted in favour of calling for Andrew Lansley's resignation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/bma-demands-andrew-lansley-resignation-7896267.html |website=The Independent |title=BMA demands Andrew Landsley's resignation |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Doctors voted in agreement of a motion stating \"This meeting has no confidence in Andrew Lansley, the Secretary of State for Health, and calls for him to resign\". In the meeting, Lansley was accused by the BMA of \"breaching doctors' trust\" over pension agreements, and was accused by Dr Gary Marlowe who tabled the motion that \"during the election he (Lansley) misled the public and the profession\" regarding the Health and Social Care Bill. Before voting, Marlowe also stated that \"The Bill went through a stunning number of amendments and revisions. I believe the most of any Bill. How can we trust someone with such a poor record with our NHS?\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/9361821/BMA-conference-doctors-threaten-new-strike-over-pensions.html |website=The Daily Telegraph |title=BMA conference doctors threaten new strike over pensions |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012|last1=Smith |first1=Rebecca }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2012, Lansley was moved out of his role as Health Secretary into the position of [[Lord Privy Seal]].\n\n==Salt reduction==\nIn 2010 Nutrition policy was transferred to the Department of Health. As Secretary of State for Health, Andrew Lansley was accused by the BMJ of allowing the food industry to stall progress in reducing salt content in food (subsequently restarted in 2014 by [[Anna Soubry]] with publication of new targets effective in 2017).<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.h1936 |pmid=25922339 |title=Food and the responsibility deal: How the salt reduction strategy was derailed |journal=BMJ |volume=350 |pages=h1936 |year=2015 |last1=MacGregor |first1=G. A |last2=He |first2=F. J |last3=Pombo-Rodrigues |first3=S }}</ref>\n\n==Public behaviour==\n[[File:Lansley poster at 2011 protests.JPG|thumb|right|A poster critical of Lansley being carried during the [[2011 anti-cuts protest in London]].]]\n\n===Suggested conflicts of interest===\nUntil December 2009, Lansley received \u00a3134 an hour from a firm of advertisers that represents clients such as [[Walkers (snack foods)|Walkers Crisps]], [[McDonald's]], [[Unilever]], [[Mars, Incorporated|Mars]] and [[Pizza Hut]]; ''[[Private Eye]]'' suggests a link between these activities and Lansley's desire to see a more lightly regulated food industry.<ref name=\"pe1267\">{{cite magazine|title=HP Sauce|magazine=[[Private Eye]]|date=23 July \u2013 5 August 2010|issue=1267|page=6}}</ref> The same publication suggested a similar link to a Department of Health report on red meat in which the only products listed in the report found to contain suitable amounts of red meat to merit a \"Good\" rating were a ''McDonald's [[Big Mac]]'', and a [[Peperami]] (manufactured by Unilever).\n\nWhile in opposition as health spokesman, Andrew Lansley accepted a donation of \u00a321,000 from [[John Nash, Baron Nash|John Nash]], the chairman of private healthcare provider [[Care UK]] and founder of the private equity fund Sovereign Capital, which owns several other private healthcare companies, to help fund his private office, leading to allegations of a conflict of interest.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/6989408/Andrew-Lansley-bankrolled-by-private-healthcare-provider.html |title=Andrew Lansley bankrolled by private healthcare provider |website=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 January 2010 |accessdate=6 April 2011}}</ref> Such companies stand to be the largest beneficiaries of Lansley's bill passed by the Coalition and [[House of Lords]] to increase the use of private health providers within the NHS.<ref>{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Holly |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/6989408/Andrew-Lansley-bankrolled-by-private-healthcare-provider.html |title=Andrew Lansley bankrolled by private healthcare provider|work=The Daily Telegraph|date= 14 January 2010|accessdate=14 January 2011|location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110125054040/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/6989408/Andrew-Lansley-bankrolled-by-private-healthcare-provider.html| archivedate= 25 January 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs reported February 2011, Lansley's wife advised attendees at a business conference to \"establish positive relationships with decision-makers\". Although staff members of Low Associates, the PR firm she runs, had food and drug companies among their clients before joining Low Associates, the firm denies it has any clients in the health sector.<ref name=\"Wife lobbying\">{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Holly |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8305506/Wife-of-Health-Secretary-Andrew-Lansley-gave-lobbying-advice.html |title=Wife of Health Secretary Andrew Lansley gave lobbying advice |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 February 2011 |accessdate=30 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311013846/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8305506/Wife-of-Health-Secretary-Andrew-Lansley-gave-lobbying-advice.html|archivedate=11 March 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAndrew Lansley's wife, Sally Low, is the managing director of Low Associates. Sally Low denies that Low Associates is involved in lobbying and instead describes its activities as provision of \"strategic advice\" to clients. Low Associates helps people prepare before they give evidence to committees of MPs, and Sally Low has given speeches on improving lobbying skills, in which she said that lobbyists should \"establish positive relationships with decision-makers before you need their help\". Lobbyist clients of Low Associates personnel have previously worked for a variety of companies including those with an interest in health, such as [[GlaxoSmithKline|SmithKline Beecham]], Unilever and Procter & Gamble.<ref name=\"Wife lobbying\"/>\n\n===Recession===\nAndrew Lansley wrote a blog entry on the Conservative Party website on 25 November 2008, which claimed the \"good things\" from a recession included people being able to spend more time with their families.<ref>[http://www.recessmonkey.com/2008/11/25/lost-your-job-well-at-least-you-will-see-more-of-your-family/ Recess Monkey]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107151538/http://www.recessmonkey.com/2008/11/25/lost-your-job-well-at-least-you-will-see-more-of-your-family/ |date=7 January 2009 }}</ref> He was later forced to apologise.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7748085.stm | work=BBC News | title=Lansley's recession blog apology | date=25 November 2008 | accessdate=25 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary expenses===\nIn the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|Parliamentary expenses scandal]] in 2009, Lansley was accused of 'flipping', or redesignating, his second home, after claiming for renovation of a rural cottage prior to selling it. It is claimed that he then 'flipped' his second home designation to a London flat, and claimed thousands of pounds for furniture. Lansley responded to the claims by stating that his claims were \"within the rules\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rayner |first=Gordon |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5305406/Andrew-Lansley-sold-home-after-expenses-renovations.html |title=Andrew Lansley sold home after expenses renovations\n|work=The Daily Telegraph |date= 11 May 2009|accessdate=14 May 2009 |location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090514070251/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5305406/Andrew-Lansley-sold-home-after-expenses-renovations.html| archivedate= 14 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> He owns a Pimlico property, but has claimed over \u00a37000 for hotel stays.\n\n==House of Lords==\nLansley was created a [[Life Peer]] taking the title '''Baron Lansley''', ''of [[Orwell, Cambridgeshire|Orwell]] in the County of [[Cambridgeshire]]'' on 5 October 2015.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61375 |date=8 October 2015 |page=18926}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLansley married his first wife Marilyn Biggs in 1985 and they had three daughters.<ref name=\"walked\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/andrew-lansley-it-would-let-people-down-if-i-just-walked-away-6278843.html|title=Andrew Lansley: 'It would let people down if I just walked away'|last=Chorley|first=Matt|date=18 December 2011|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref> They divorced in 2001 and Lansley married Sally Low, with whom he has had a son and a daughter.<ref name=walked/> Lansley's wealth was estimated at \u00a3700,000 in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |author=Samira Shackle, Stephanie Hegarty and George Eaton |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2009/10/oxford-universitywealth-school |title = The new ruling class |work=New Statesman |date=1 October 2009|accessdate=4 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 Lansley revealed that he has [[Cancer staging|stage 3]] [[bowel cancer]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Greenfield|first1=Patrick|title=Lord Lansley calls for better screening after revealing cancer|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/apr/03/lord-lansley-calls-for-better-screening-after-revealing-cancer|accessdate=3 April 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 April 2018}}</ref> He has called for the government to widen the [[cancer screening]] programme on the NHS.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andrew Lansley}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110729105138/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Lansley_Andrew.aspx Profile] at the Conservative Party\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = andrew-lansley/123 | hansard = mr-andrew-lansley | hansardcurr = 1419 | guardian = 3010/andrew-lansley | publicwhip = Andrew_Lansley | theywork = andrew_lansley | record = Andrew-Lansley/South-Cambridgeshire/286 | bbc = 25555.stm | journalisted = andrew-lansley }}\n*{{Guardian topic}}\n*[http://www.thefutureofthenhs.com The Future of the NHS]\n*[http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/20501/Andrew-David-LANSLEY ''Debrett's People of Today'']{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[South Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Cambridgeshire]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Heidi Allen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Shadow Minister for the Cabinet Office]]|years=1999\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tim Collins (politician)|Tim Collins]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Yeo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]|years=2004\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andy Burnham]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andy Burnham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Health]]|years=2010\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeremy Hunt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Sir George Young|George Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the House of Commons]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Hague]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Privy Seal]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Tina Stowell, Baroness Stowell of Beeston|The Baroness Stowell of Beeston]]}}}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stuart Polak, Baron Polak|The Lord Polak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Lansley'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Jonathan Oates, Baron Oates|The Lord Oates]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Cabinet of David Cameron}}\n{{Leader of the House of Commons}}\n{{Secretary of State for Health}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lansley, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Exeter]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Department of Trade and Industry]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by David Cameron]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brentwood School, Essex]]\n[[Category:People from Hornchurch]]\n[[Category:Private secretaries in the British Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Health (UK)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eShadow Cabinet:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Lansley"}
{"title_page": "Elham Malekpoor Arashlu", "text_new": "{{notability|1=Biographies|date=September 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1983|7|}}\n| image       = Elham_Malekpoor.jpg\n| birth_place = [[Iran]]\n| occupation  = Human rights activist, journalist and poet\n| residence   = [[The Netherlands]]\n| nationality = Iranian\n| website = [http://elhammalekpoor.com elhammalekpoor.com]\n}}\n\n'''Elham Malekpoor Arashlu''' ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u200c\u067e\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0631\u0634\u0644\u0648}}) or '''Elham Malepoor''' is an Iranian poet, writer and journalist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elham Malekpoor Arashlu|url=https://rfgmagazine.nl/author/elham-malekpoor-arashlu/|website=RFG Magazine|language=Dutch}}</ref> She was born in Iran and she is semi-blind.<ref name=\"rzel\">{{cite news |last1=\u0633\u0645\u0631\u0642\u0646\u062f\u06cc |first1=\u0634\u0647\u0632\u0627\u062f\u0647 |title=\u0648\u0642\u062a\u06cc \u0634\u0627\u0639\u0631 \u0633\u06a9\u0648\u062a\u0634 \u0631\u0627 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0634\u06a9\u0646\u062f |url=https://www.radiozamaneh.com/373925 |publisher=\u0631\u0627\u062f\u06cc\u0648 \u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0647 |date=15 January 2018 |language=Persian |quote=\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u200c\u067e\u0648\u0631 \u0631\u0627 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0642\u06cc\u0645 \u0627\u0631\u0648\u067e\u0627 \u0628\u0647\u200c \u0639\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u0627 \u062a\u0648\u0627\u0646\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u062f\u0648\u062f \u0628\u06cc\u0646\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0648 \u0645\u062f\u0627\u0641\u0639 \u067e\u0631\u06a9\u0627\u0631 \u062d\u0642\u0648\u0642 \u06a9\u0648\u062f\u06a9 \u0648 \u0627\u0642\u0644\u06cc\u062a\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u062c\u0646\u0633\u06cc \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0634\u0646\u0627\u0633\u0646\u062f.}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nElham was born in July 1983 in Iran. She graduated from Kerman University in [[Persian literature]]. She lives in [[the Netherlands]] and works as a [[LGBT Rights]] activist, writer, and poet.<ref name=\"rzel\" />\n\nElham left Iran in September 2012 due to threats against her.<ref>{{cite web |title=Poems in Exile: Elham Malekpoor |url=http://www.sampsoniaway.org/literary-voices/2015/02/03/poems-in-exile-elham-malekpoor/ |website=Sampsonia Way |date=3 February 2015}}</ref> She has been a member of [[PEN International]] in the Netherlands since 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conceptnotulen ALV 2016 |url=https://pennederland.nl/conceptnotulen-alv-2016 |website=PEN Nederland |language=Dutch}}</ref> Elham worked in [[JoopeA|JoopeA Foundation]] as a member of management team from 2015 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elham Malekpoor Introduction |url=https://joopea.info/?p=38 |website=JoopeA |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\nElham published her first book of poems ''Jamaica is a country too...'' ({{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0647 \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0626\u06cc\u06a9\u0627 \u0647\u0645 \u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u200c\u0633\u062a...}}) in 2006 in Iran.<ref>{{cite web |author1=\u0645\u0627\u0647\u06cc |title=\u0646\u06af\u0631\u0647 \u0648 \u0646\u0642\u062f\u06cc \u0628\u0631 \u0627\u062f\u0628\u06cc\u0627\u062a \u062f\u06af\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0634 |url=http://www.iran-chabar.de/article.jsp?essayId=40740 |website=Akhbare-rooz |language=Persian |date=27 September 2011 |quote=\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u200c\u067e\u0648\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u0633\u0627\u0644 1385 \u0645\u062c\u0645\u0648\u0639\u0647 \u0634\u0639\u0631\u06cc \u0628\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u0645 \u00ab\u06a9\u0647 \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0626\u06cc\u06a9\u0627 \u0647\u0645 \u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u200c\u0633\u062a...\u00bb \u0631\u0627 \u062a\u0648\u0633\u0637 \u0646\u0634\u0631 \u00ab\u0645\u0647\u0631\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0634\u00bb \u062f\u0631 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0646\u062a\u0634\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a.}}</ref>\n\nMalekpoor is also the author of the books ''A chair to sit'' ({{lang-fa|\u0635\u0646\u062f\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0646\u0634\u0633\u062a\u0646}}),<ref>{{cite web|author1=Elham Malekpoor Arashlu|title=\u0635\u0646\u062f\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0646\u0634\u0633\u062a\u0646|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bi4Oiglh9Kc/|website=Roonak Publication on Instagram|publisher=Roonak Publication|language=Persian}}</ref> ''Historiography of Homan'' ({{lang-fa|\u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e\u200c\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0647\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646}})<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631 \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e\u200c\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0647\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646|url=https://joopea.news/2018/03/homan-history-book-norouz-gift-of-joopea/|website=JNews|publisher=\u06a9\u0627\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u062e\u0628\u0631 \u0698\u0648\u067e\u06cc\u200c\u0622|language=Persian|access-date=2018-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816195952/https://joopea.news/2018/03/homan-history-book-norouz-gift-of-joopea/|archive-date=2018-08-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e\u200c\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u06af\u0631\u0648\u0647 \u0647\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646|url=https://literatuurplein.nl/detail/boek/-/1479223|website=Het Literatuurplein|language=Dutch}}</ref> and ''Breaking the invertebrate flesh'' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0646\u0642\u0627\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0648\u0634\u062a \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0645\u0647\u0631\u0647}}).<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0645\u0646\u0642\u0627\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0648\u0634\u062a \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0645\u0647\u0631\u0647|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BihcDQLh7ke/|website=Roonak Publication on Instagram|publisher=Roonak Publication|language=Persian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://elhammalekpoor.com Personal website]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arashlu, Elham Malekpoor}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:LGBT poets]]\n[[Category:Iranian journalists]]\n[[Category:Iranian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Iran]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Iran]]\n[[Category:Iranian women poets]]\n\n\n{{Iran-poet-stub}}\n{{LGBT-activist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|1=Biographies|date=September 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1983|7|}}\n| image       = Elham_Malekpoor.jpg\n| birth_place = [[Iran]]\n| occupation  = Human rights activist, journalist and poet\n| residence   = [[The Netherlands]]\n| nationality = Iranian\n| website = [http://elhammalekpoor.com elhammalekpoor.com]\n}}\n\n'''Elham Malekpoor Arashlu''' ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u200c\u067e\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0631\u0634\u0644\u0648}}) or '''Elham Malepoor''' is an Iranian poet, writer and journalist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elham Malekpoor Arashlu|url=https://rfgmagazine.nl/author/elham-malekpoor-arashlu/|website=RFG Magazine|language=Dutch}}</ref> She was born in Iran and she is semi-blind.<ref name=\"rzel\">{{cite news |last1=\u0633\u0645\u0631\u0642\u0646\u062f\u06cc |first1=\u0634\u0647\u0632\u0627\u062f\u0647 |title=\u0648\u0642\u062a\u06cc \u0634\u0627\u0639\u0631 \u0633\u06a9\u0648\u062a\u0634 \u0631\u0627 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0634\u06a9\u0646\u062f |url=https://www.radiozamaneh.com/373925 |publisher=\u0631\u0627\u062f\u06cc\u0648 \u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0647 |date=15 January 2018 |language=Persian |quote=\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u200c\u067e\u0648\u0631 \u0631\u0627 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0642\u06cc\u0645 \u0627\u0631\u0648\u067e\u0627 \u0628\u0647\u200c \u0639\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u062c\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u0627 \u062a\u0648\u0627\u0646\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u062f\u0648\u062f \u0628\u06cc\u0646\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0648 \u0645\u062f\u0627\u0641\u0639 \u067e\u0631\u06a9\u0627\u0631 \u062d\u0642\u0648\u0642 \u06a9\u0648\u062f\u06a9 \u0648 \u0627\u0642\u0644\u06cc\u062a\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u062c\u0646\u0633\u06cc \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0634\u0646\u0627\u0633\u0646\u062f.}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nElham was born in July 1983 in Iran. She graduated from Kerman University in [[Persian literature]]. She lives in [[the Netherlands]] and works as a [[LGBT Rights]] activist, writer, and poet.<ref name=\"rzel\" />\n\nElham left Iran in September 2012 due to threats against her.<ref>{{cite web |title=Poems in Exile: Elham Malekpoor |url=http://www.sampsoniaway.org/literary-voices/2015/02/03/poems-in-exile-elham-malekpoor/ |website=Sampsonia Way |date=3 February 2015}}</ref> She has been a member of [[PEN International]] in the Netherlands since 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conceptnotulen ALV 2016 |url=https://pennederland.nl/conceptnotulen-alv-2016 |website=PEN Nederland |language=Dutch}}</ref> Elham worked in [[JoopeA|JoopeA Foundation]] as a member of management team from 2015 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elham Malekpoor Introduction |url=https://joopea.info/?p=38 |website=JoopeA |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\nElham published her first book of poems ''Jamaica is a country too...'' ({{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0647 \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0626\u06cc\u06a9\u0627 \u0647\u0645 \u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u200c\u0633\u062a...}}) in 2006 in Iran.<ref>{{cite web |author1=\u0645\u0627\u0647\u06cc |title=\u0646\u06af\u0631\u0647 \u0648 \u0646\u0642\u062f\u06cc \u0628\u0631 \u0627\u062f\u0628\u06cc\u0627\u062a \u062f\u06af\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0634 |url=http://www.iran-chabar.de/article.jsp?essayId=40740 |website=Akhbare-rooz |language=Persian |date=27 September 2011 |quote=\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0644\u06a9\u200c\u067e\u0648\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u0633\u0627\u0644 1385 \u0645\u062c\u0645\u0648\u0639\u0647 \u0634\u0639\u0631\u06cc \u0628\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u0645 \u00ab\u06a9\u0647 \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0626\u06cc\u06a9\u0627 \u0647\u0645 \u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u200c\u0633\u062a...\u00bb \u0631\u0627 \u062a\u0648\u0633\u0637 \u0646\u0634\u0631 \u00ab\u0645\u0647\u0631\u0631\u0627\u0648\u0634\u00bb \u062f\u0631 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0646\u062a\u0634\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a.}}</ref>\n\nMalekpoor is also the author of the books ''A chair to sit'' ({{lang-fa|\u0635\u0646\u062f\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0646\u0634\u0633\u062a\u0646}}),<ref>{{cite web|author1=Elham Malekpoor Arashlu|title=\u0635\u0646\u062f\u0644\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0646\u0634\u0633\u062a\u0646|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bi4Oiglh9Kc/|website=Roonak Publication on Instagram|publisher=Roonak Publication|language=Persian}}</ref> ''Historiography of Homan'' ({{lang-fa|\u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e\u200c\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0647\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646}})<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631 \u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e\u200c\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u0647\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646|url=https://joopea.news/2018/03/homan-history-book-norouz-gift-of-joopea/|website=JNews|publisher=\u06a9\u0627\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u062e\u0628\u0631 \u0698\u0648\u067e\u06cc\u200c\u0622|language=Persian|access-date=2018-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816195952/https://joopea.news/2018/03/homan-history-book-norouz-gift-of-joopea/|archive-date=2018-08-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e\u200c\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u06af\u0631\u0648\u0647 \u0647\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646|url=https://literatuurplein.nl/detail/boek/-/1479223|website=Het Literatuurplein|language=Dutch}}</ref> and ''Breaking the invertebrate flesh'' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0646\u0642\u0627\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0648\u0634\u062a \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0645\u0647\u0631\u0647}}).<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0645\u0646\u0642\u0627\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0648\u0634\u062a \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0645\u0647\u0631\u0647|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BihcDQLh7ke/|website=Roonak Publication on Instagram|publisher=Roonak Publication|language=Persian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://elhammalekpoor.com Personal website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arashlu, Elham Malekpoor}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:LGBT poets]]\n[[Category:Iranian journalists]]\n[[Category:Iranian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Iran]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Iran]]\n[[Category:Iranian women poets]]\n\n\n{{Iran-poet-stub}}\n{{LGBT-activist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elham_Malekpoor_Arashlu"}
